== A History of Ziv and Lempel

#history[
  *Abraham Lempel* (born 1936) and *Jacob Ziv* (born 1931) were both professors
  at the Technion (Israel Institute of Technology in Haifa). They met at MIT in
  the late 1950s, and their collaboration spanned decades. Their 1977 and 1978
  papers were not immediately recognized as revolutionary; the information theory
  community at the time was focused on probabilistic models. But by the mid-1980s,
  practitioners realized: here was a compressor that *worked*, needed no training
  data, and was fast enough to run in software.

  Terry Welch's 1984 LZW paper (Chapter 29) brought LZ78 into mass use via the
  Unix `compress` program and GIF. The subsequent patent battles over LZW
  (the Unisys GIF firestorm) would ironically accelerate the spread of LZ77 via
  DEFLATE, which Phil Katz deliberately made patent-free.

  Jacob Ziv won the IEEE Medal of Honor in 1995. Lempel was awarded the IEEE
  Richard W. Hamming Medal in 1996. Together, in 2004, they received the Marconi
  Prize (sometimes called the "Nobel Prize of communications"). Their two papers
  remain among the ten most-cited works in the history of information theory.
]

== Variants and the LZ Family Tree

The LZ77 and LZ78 papers seeded an enormous family of algorithms. Here is a
concise map:

*LZ77 descendants:*
- *LZSS* (1982, Storer–Szymanski): flag bits, no literal appended to a match.
- *DEFLATE* (1991, Phil Katz): LZSS + two-level Huffman coding. Chapter 30.
- *LZRW* (1991, Ross Williams): a fast, simple LZ77 for embedded systems.
- *LZO* (1996, Markus Oberhumer): speed-focused, designed for in-memory use.
- *LZ4* (2011, Yann Collet): near-memcpy decode speed, no entropy coding.
- *LZMA* (1998–, Igor Pavlov): LZ77 + range coding + huge window. 7-Zip/xz. Chapter 31.
- *Zstandard* (2016, Yann Collet): LZ77 + ANS (FSE) + trained dictionaries. Chapter 32.
- *Brotli* (2013–2015, Google): LZ77 + static web dictionary + Huffman. Chapter 32.

*LZ78 descendants:*
- *LZW* (1984, Terry Welch): simplifies LZ78 by folding the literal into the table. Chapter 29.
- *LZMW* (1985, Miller–Wegman): concatenates two existing phrases.
- *LZC*: Unix `compress`'s variant of LZW with dictionary clearing.
- *LZJ*, *LZAP*: less common research variants.

#aside[
  Why did LZ77 win the long game over LZ78? Two reasons. First, the patent on
  LZW (a LZ78 descendant) poisoned the LZ78 branch from 1985 to ~2003, pushing
  engineers toward LZ77-based designs. Second, LZ77's sliding-window model
  naturally bounds memory, while LZ78's growing dictionary can balloon without
  bound. When Collet designed Zstandard, he stayed firmly in the LZ77 camp.
  Trained dictionaries gave zstd the LZ78-like ability to share prefix
  knowledge without the unbounded-memory problem.
]

== Why Dictionary Coding Works on Real Data

Real data is not random. English text repeats words, phrases, and grammatical
patterns. HTML repeats tags and attributes. Machine code repeats instruction
patterns. Executables repeat function prologues. The LZ77 sliding window
exploits all of these because it captures *whatever patterns appear in the recent
context*, with no prior knowledge of the data type.

To make this concrete, consider what a 32 KB window "sees" inside a typical
data file:

- *English text:* common words (`the`, `and`, `of`, `to`) repeat within almost
  every sentence. Function words reappear every few hundred bytes. A 32 KB
  window covering roughly 5,000 words of text will find these words and phrases
  almost every time they appear.
- *HTML/CSS/JS:* tags like `<div>`, `class="`, `return false`, and `function(`
  repeat hundreds of times per file. LZ77 replaces every repeated occurrence
  with a short (distance, length) pair.
- *Binary executables:* function prologues (`push rbp`, `mov rbp, rsp` in
  x86-64) and common byte patterns repeat across the file. Even machine code,
  which looks random to the eye, has abundant low-level structure.
- *Log files:* timestamps follow predictable patterns; error messages repeat
  verbatim; hostnames and stack-trace class names are constant.

This adaptivity is the magic. A Huffman coder needs to know the frequency of
each byte value to assign short codes. LZ77 needs to know nothing in advance
It just notices "I have seen this before" and points back to it.

#misconception[
  "LZ77 is just run-length encoding."
][
  Run-length encoding (RLE) handles repetitions of *single symbols*: `aaaaaa`
  becomes `(a, 6)`. LZ77 handles repetitions of *arbitrary substrings* at
  arbitrary distances: `the fox the fox` becomes a reference to an 8-byte match.
  LZ77 strictly generalizes RLE: the overlap-copy trick we saw under
  _"Decoding Is Trivial"_ makes
  LZ77 subsume RLE as a special case, but LZ77 can do vastly more.
]

The universality proof tells us that, asymptotically, dictionary coding is as
good as any lossless compressor on any stationary ergodic source. But the
*rate of convergence* matters enormously in practice. LZ77 with a 32 KB window
needs millions of bytes before it fully adapts; on small files it can be worse
than a well-designed Huffman coder. This is why DEFLATE's gzip uses LZ77
*first* (to remove cross-symbol patterns) and Huffman *second* (to remove
remaining within-token redundancy).

=== The LZSS Token Cost Analysis

To understand when a back-reference is profitable, let us think about the *bit
cost* of each token type in a concrete format.

In DEFLATE (which we will build in Chapter 30), tokens are encoded as follows:

- *Literals:* each literal byte is coded with a Huffman code drawn from an
  alphabet of 256 byte values plus a special end-of-block symbol. At typical
  English text frequencies, common bytes like space (` `) and `e` get codes of
  7–8 bits; rare bytes might get 12–15 bits. The average is roughly 7–8 bits
  per literal byte.

- *Match tokens:* a match of length $ell$ and distance $d$ is coded as:
  - A *length code* (drawn from a Huffman alphabet of 29 codes), typically 7–9 bits.
  - A few *extra bits* for the precise length within a range (0–5 extra bits).
  - A *distance code* (a second Huffman alphabet of 30 codes), typically 5–7 bits.
  - More *extra bits* for the precise distance (0–13 extra bits).

  Total: roughly 15–30 bits to represent a match of any length.

The break-even is therefore: a match of length $ell$ is worth emitting when
$ell times 8 > 20$ bits (the typical match token cost), i.e., $ell >= 3$ bytes.
A 3-byte match saves about $3 times 8 - 20 = 4$ bits; a 10-byte match saves
$10 times 8 - 20 = 60$ bits; a 258-byte (maximum) match saves over 2,000 bits.

This is why long matches are so valuable, and why compressors try hard to find
them. The hash-chain search is optimizing for this: find the *longest* match,
because the bit saving grows with match length while the overhead stays
nearly constant.

== Practical Considerations: Window Size, Compression Levels, and Speed

Practitioners face constant trade-offs across four dimensions: *ratio* (how
small the output is), *encode speed* (how fast compression runs), *decode speed*
(how fast decompression runs), and *memory* (how much RAM the encoder and decoder
need). No algorithm is best on all four simultaneously.

=== Window Size

*Window size* determines how far back a reference can reach. A 32 KB window
(DEFLATE) suffices for most text and HTML. A 512 KB window (LZ4 high) or an
8 MB window (LZMA) catches repetitions in larger files: firmware, executables,
and archives. Larger windows cost more memory for *both* encoder and decoder.

To illustrate: on a 100 MB virtual machine disk image, the Linux kernel is
included in multiple forms (source, object files, installed binary). The kernel
is self-similar across these representations: the same string constants,
function names, and header file contents repeat at intervals of tens of
megabytes. A 32 KB window *cannot* see these far-away repetitions; a 64 MB
window *can*. This is why xz (`--lzma2`) at maximum settings uses a 64 MB window
and achieves dramatically better ratios than gzip on software archives, at the
cost of needing 64 MB of RAM in the decoder.

=== Compression Levels

*Compression levels* in tools like gzip (`-1` to `-9`) and zstd (`-1` to `22`)
mainly control two parameters: (a) how hard the encoder searches for matches
(hash chain depth vs. suffix-tree search), and (b) whether lazy matching is
used. Level 1 is fast but finds short matches; level 9 or 22 exhaustively
searches for the longest match at every position.

A useful mental model: think of compression levels as a *time budget* for the
encoder. At level 1, the encoder looks at the hash chain but stops after 8
candidates. At level 9, it walks the entire chain (up to 4,096 candidates per
position in zlib). The data is the same; the encoder just works harder to find
better matches. The ratio improvement from level 1 to level 9 is typically
10–20% for typical files, useful but not dramatic. The speed difference can
be 10–50 times.

=== Decode Speed: The Asymmetry That Won the Web

*Decode speed is always fast* regardless of compression level. That asymmetry defines LZ77. A decoder needs only a ring buffer and simple byte-copy
operations. There is no search to do; just "jump to position, copy bytes." On
modern hardware, DEFLATE decompression runs at 400–600 MB/s in software. LZ4
decodes at multi-gigabytes per second. The encoder might be 20× slower than
the decoder.

This asymmetry is why DEFLATE became the format of the web. Servers (or build
pipelines) compress CSS, JS, and HTML once, perhaps at level 9. Billions of
clients decompress in milliseconds. The encoder pays once; every reader benefits.

#keyidea[
  LZ77 compression is encoder-heavy, decoder-light. You pay the search cost
  once at compression time; decoding costs only memory bandwidth. This is the
  perfect trade-off for the web, where servers compress once and clients
  decompress millions of times per day.
]

